description: THERE is a message in ''Children of Babylon,'' but it is pretty well buried under a morass of inconsequential talk, heavy-handed humor, soft-core pornography and haphazard organization. 'RESURRECTION' HAS THE MANNER OF A FAIRY TALE
description: ''RESURRECTION'' is a movie about faith, and one that must be taken on faith. It's a little bit mad. But it has the courage of its conviction, and a beauty and persuasiveness that help keep the doubts at bay. You may not be far out of the theater before the film begins to seem silly. But the measure of its sincerity is the experience of watching it, which is a very uncomplicated one. Believe, the movie says, and for a while you really do.

A CANINE DETECTIVE
description: Heaven isn't a place worth going to, if ''Oh Heavenly Dog'' is to be believed. When a private investigator, played by Chevy Chase, is killed in the line of duty, he arrives in a facsimile of a Government office, except the decor is white instead of green. A computer -in Heaven! a computer! - gives him a personal identification code, and then he stands on line in a crowded waiting room, hoping for reassignment to a new body. The body he gets is that of Benji, hence the movie's title.

description: TAKING as his starting point the troubled life of Jake La Motta, the tough New York City kid who slugged his way to the world middleweight boxing championship in 1948 and then went on to lose almost everything, Martin Scorsese (''Mean Streets,'' ''Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore,'' ''Taxi Driver'') has made his most ambitious film as well as his finest. Though ''Raging Bull'' has only three principal characters, it is a big film, its territory being the landscape of the soul.

'IDOLMAKER'CREATES A TEEN STAR
description: LIKE ''The Buddy Holly Story,'' ''The Idolmaker'' is a page torn - politely - from the annals of rock-and-roll history. And, like ''The Buddy Holly Story,'' it hinges on a central performance that is much better than the movie around it. Ray Sharkey, playing a rock Svengali in the days of Frankie and Bobby and Dion and Fabian, captures the drive and monomania of a man who shapes others' destinies rather than his own. In those days, it took looks to be a teen idol - or so the movie, with some cynicism, maintains. Mr. Sharkey's Vincent Vacarri is a man of talent, and so he becomes a manager instead of a star.

'SPACE MOVIE' TELLS ASTRONAUT STORY
description: WHEN they stopped making psychedelic films some years ago, they stopped for a reason. A spongy state of mind is the requisite for watching something like Tony Palmer's ''The Space Movie,'' which is a throwback to a sensibility long gone. Mr. Palmer has compiled footage from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the National Archives, piled on a lulling musical accompaniment, and invited his audience to lay back and groove. They may yawn instead.

'HEAVEN'S GATE,' A WESTERN BY CIMINO
description: ''HEAVEN'S GATE,'' Michael Cimino's gigantic new western and his first film since the Oscar-winning ''The Deer Hunter,'' is apparently based on a historical incident that occured in Johnson County, Wyo. in 1890: with the tacit approval of the state government, the county's wealthy cattle barons banded together in a systematic attempt to murder more than 100 German, Bulgarian, Russian and Ukrainian settlers who were encroaching on their lands. If one can say nothing else on behalf of ''Heaven's Gate'' (and I certainly can't), it's probably the first western to celebrate the role played by central and eastern Europeans in the settlement of the American West.

'FALLING IN LOVE,' PRECOCIOUS PRODUCTION
description: LACKING the talent of Stephen Crane, who wrote ''The Red Badge of Courage'' without ever having been to war, Steven Paul, a former child actor, has not unexpectedly made a botch of ''Falling in Love Again.'' The comedy, about the midlife crisis of a man in his 40's, was conceived by Mr. Paul when he was 18 years old and finished when he was 21, financed, apparently, by an indulgent family and friends. His knowledge of the world appears to have come exclusively from bad television situation comedies.
